<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10070e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10070e">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10070e"> 70(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dot &amp; dash / click / Morse</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Vail se dit qu&apos;il fallait le <font color="green">[= l&apos;appareil typographique]</font> compl&eacute;ter en combinant un syst&egrave;me de traits plus ou moins allong&eacute;s, de points et de blancs interpos&eacute;s pour repr&eacute;senter les lettres de l&apos;alphabet et la s&eacute;paration des mots. Il r&eacute;gla ainsi un code de signes t&eacute;l&eacute;graphiques, qu&apos;on appelle improprement l&apos;<mark>Alphabet de Morse</mark> &hellip; et qui est devenu par la suite le langage t&eacute;l&eacute;graphique du monde entier. <font color="green">[The first typographical machine was built at Speedwell [&hellip;]</font> in the State of New Jersey.<font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Vail thought it was necessary to complete it by devising a system with dashes of various lengths, dots, and interposed blanks representing letters of the alphabet and the separation of words. In this way he created a code for telegraphic signs, which we improperly call the Morse Code <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> and which has since become the telegraphic language for the whole world.] <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 334-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01034d" href="c01all.htm#c01034d">VI.C.01:034(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
